Supervised Learning Project - Thera Bank Personal Loan (Banking)¶

Attribute Information:

  • ID : Customer ID
  • Age : Customer's age in completed years
  • Experience : #years of professional experience
  • Income : Annual income of the customer
  • ZIP Code : Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family : Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg : Avg. spending on credit cards per month
  • Education : Education Level.
    1. Undergrad
    2. Graduate
    3. Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage : Value of house mortgage if any.
  • Personal Loan : Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities Account : Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD Account : Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online : Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  • Credit card : Does the customer use a credit card issued by UniversalBank?

  11. CreditCard - Categorical(Binary) variable. Number of people without Credit card is more than people with Credit card.
  12. ZIP Code - Uniform distribution

Observations - Age has a very strong positive correlation with Experience

Since Age has a strong positive association with Experience, we can replace the negative Experience of a particular Age with the Median of Experience of that Age in the non-negative dataset

In [15]:
df_Possitive_Experience = dataset[dataset['Experience'] > 0]
df_Negative_Experience =  dataset[dataset['Experience'] < 0]
df_Negative_Experience_List = df_Negative_Experience['ID'].tolist()

for id in df_Negative_Experience_List:
    age_values = dataset.loc[np.where(dataset['ID']==id)]["Age"].tolist()[0]
    possitive_Filtered = df_Possitive_Experience[(df_Possitive_Experience['Age'] == age_values)]
    if possitive_Filtered.empty:
        negative_Filtered = df_Negative_Experience[(df_Negative_Experience['Age'] == age_values)]
        exp = round(negative_Filtered['Experience'].median())
    else:
        exp = round(possitive_Filtered['Experience'].median())
    dataset.loc[dataset.loc[np.where(dataset['ID']==id)].index, 'Experience'] = abs(exp)

Higher the AUC, more preferred the model is. In the above plot, it appears that the AUC for Logistic regression is the best here.

Comparing Precision, Recall and F1 score¶

Precision¶

When a positive value is predicted, how often is the prediction correct?

In [52]:
prec_log = (log_cm[1][1])/(log_cm[1][1] + log_cm[0][1])
prec_knn = (knn_cm[1][1])/(knn_cm[1][1] + knn_cm[0][1])
prec_nb = (nb_cm[1][1])/(nb_cm[1][1] + nb_cm[0][1])
print('Precision for Logistic regression :', round(prec_log,2))
print('Precision for KNN                 :', round(prec_knn,2))
print('Precision for Naive Bayes         :', round(prec_nb,1))

Precision for Logistic regression : 0.86
Precision for KNN                 : 0.99
Precision for Naive Bayes         : 0.4

Recall¶

When the actual value is positive, how often is the prediction correct?

In [53]:
rec_log = (log_cm[1][1])/(log_cm[1][1] + log_cm[1][0])
rec_knn = (knn_cm[1][1])/(knn_cm[1][1] + knn_cm[1][0])
rec_nb = (nb_cm[1][1])/(nb_cm[1][1] + nb_cm[1][0])
print('Recall for Logistic regression :', round(rec_log, 2))
print('Recall for KNN                 :', round(rec_knn, 2))
print('Recall for Naive Bayes         :', round(rec_nb, 2))

Recall for Logistic regression : 0.57
Recall for KNN                 : 0.47
Recall for Naive Bayes         : 0.56

F1 score¶

F1 score is the Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall

In [54]:
F1_log = 2*(prec_log*rec_log)/(prec_log + rec_log)
F1_knn = 2*(prec_knn*rec_knn)/(prec_knn + rec_knn)
F1_nb = 2*(prec_nb*rec_nb)/(prec_nb + rec_nb)
print('F1 score for Logistic regression :', round(F1_log, 2))
print('F1 score for KNN                 :', round(F1_knn, 2))
print('F1 score for Naive Bayes         :', round(F1_nb, 2))

F1 score for Logistic regression : 0.69
F1 score for KNN                 : 0.64
F1 score for Naive Bayes         : 0.47

Final thoughts:-¶

As shown in the plot above the Logistic Regression is the best model to use for this dataset. We should prefer this because:-

  1. The accuracy score of the Training data set is very close to the accuracy score of the testing data set. This ensures stability of the model for unknown data.
  2. The ROC-AUC is also the best for this model.
  3. The precision and recall accuracy scores are high.
  4. Best F1 score

For KNN, there is a small difference in the Training and test set accuracy. The Precision value is very high but recall is lower than Logistic regression and also the overall F1 score is lesser. The ROC area under the curve is the least here as well.

For Naive Bayes, the overall accuracy is less as compared to other two algorithms. The precision is very low although the recall value is similar to Logistic regression. The overall F1 score is the least.
